  title: Memorial of Remonstrance Upon Taking Office as Prefect of Gyerim
  author: Lee Dal-choong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Your servant humbly speaks. In the seventh month of autumn in the year Ding-Wei of the Zhizheng era, I received command to go forth as Prefect of Gyerim. I submitted remonstrance on grounds of illness a second time, yet did not receive approval. In trepidation, I proceeded to my post. The seasons have turned, and gazing upward at the radiance of office, one day feels like three autumns. How much more so for one like me, whose wisdom is shallow and talent sparse—though I remain long in this position, surely I will achieve nothing. I earnestly request to be relieved of this duty, unable to contain my anxiety and dread.

    Heaven and earth nurture all things without distinction between the great and small. Sun and moon illuminate all lands without failing to reach the distant and the near. Though I serve as prefect in a far province, how could your majesty's wisdom be obstructed by my earnest petition? I reflect upon my family's lineage. Both my paternal and maternal sides have known humble circumstances, possessing no special talents save learning in classical texts, which I have devoted to serving the state. Though my family has produced no one of remarkable brilliance to astound the world, neither have we brought shame upon our household or our service to the throne. Generation after generation, we have maintained our name without interruption.

    My grandfather Sae-gi and his elder brothers all became renowned in their time. When our loyal King Chungnyeol honored learning and virtue, he personally examined the literary scholars of the era and instituted the examination called the Heavenly Field Examination. Among them, Minister Jo Gan-jung placed first, my grandfather's elder brother Bang-yeon placed second, and my grandfather Sae-gi placed third. The rest were all men of note, and the king called them his "disciples of learning." In the year of Dae-deok, he commanded Minister Kim Tae-hyeon to oversee the National Examination, and my father Cheon achieved first place. The king said, "This is the son of my disciple of learning. He lost his father young yet carries on his father's legacy—how remarkable!" That very day he appointed my father to office, and thus my father advanced through the ranks, serving successive reigns and eventually becoming Prime Minister.

    I inherited the grace of this legacy. Born in the year of King Chungson, I achieved success in the civil examination under King Chungsuk. Favored by exceptional kindness, I entered service, beginning in the Secretariat before rapidly ascending to the rank of Admonishing Official. I participated in state deliberations and suddenly found myself among those tasked with the royal testament—like an orphaned child bereft of parents. The grief caught in my throat cannot be spoken.

    After this, whether serving or retiring, I never rose beyond the ranks of minor officials, until by grace of the enlightened sovereign, within but a few years I was elevated to the rank of Grand Commandant Assisting the Throne. No post I have held was ever fitting for one of my capabilities. To enumerate the reasons for these appointments would be self-aggrandizement; to list accomplishments would invite ridicule. I possess not the slightest merit, yet have been promoted thus. Surely those close to the throne, knowing my clumsiness and perceiving my ignorance, have mentioned my name during times of leisure when discussing matters of appointment, and the sovereign has graciously not forgotten.

    Since the military campaigns began, one like me has contributed nothing. My old residence in the city was consumed by the flames of the Red Turbans, leaving me homeless. I have withdrawn to the mountains for many years now. Yet my humble heart has never strayed from the throne. At my window, before my simple desk, I respectfully burn incense; before the imperial records and precious charts, I constantly pray for ten thousand years of imperial life. This has become my daily sustenance in these remaining years.

    How could I have anticipated that you would specially send forth your decree and summon me to high office? In alarm I hastened to your call, accepted your grace with shame, and proceeded forward bearing embarrassment. My aged and withered form cannot be concealed; my simple-minded nature grows ever more apparent. In the selection of officials, each position requires different talents. To obstruct the path of the worthy is deeply improper. I fear the accusation of neglecting duty, yet I receive the command to share your burdens.

    Having received this command, I have secretly reflected thus: that one as unfit as I should be repeatedly promoted can only be because your majesty takes pity upon me—there is no other patron or advocate responsible. My gratitude before heaven and earth is as boundless as the sun itself. Yet my years advance—though not yet to extreme old age, my many illnesses make me like the willow that dreads autumn. My remaining days are precious as the setting sun. I have twice submitted requests for relief, yet received no permission. How dare I presume to govern alone even for half a month? My yearning constantly turns toward the southern mountains.

    Moreover, this district is where the province converges; its affairs are truly burdensome and its reputation easily damaged. When judging disputes between two parties, once justice and injustice become clear, decision falls to one side—how can both parties be fully satisfied? In the matter of truth and falsehood, reward and punishment have already become entangled. The truthful do not feel rewarded for their truth; the punished multiply their deceptions from spite. Because deception multiplies, the situation becomes fearful. Because reward is not felt, people resort to flattery. The harmony between ruler and minister is not something I dare aspire to; the charge that my salary is drawn from the people's blood—how can I escape this?

    I humbly beseech your majesty: understand my anxiety, take pity upon my sincerity, transfer me from this post, and grant my wish. Then I shall expound upon the sage classics, instruct the rising generation, aid the state, and bathed in your benevolence, pray for your ten thousand years of life. My words have become excessive; my transgression admits no pardon.
  footnotes:
    - The 'radiance of office' (耿光) is a classical allusion to the imperial presence—serving near the throne fills even a day with the weight of three autumns.
    - The 'Heavenly Field Examination' (天場及第) was a prestigious civil service examination instituted by King Chungnyeol of Goryeo.
    - The 'Red Turbans' (紅巾賊) were rebel forces that invaded Goryeo during the mid-14th century.
    - The reference to 'the willow that dreads autumn' draws from classical Chinese poetry about aging and decline.
    - The 'southern mountains' allude to withdrawal from official life and return to simplicity—here expressing the author's longing to retire.
